<td>
<div class="content-box pad-box-micro border border-b border-t" style="background-color: whitesmoke;">
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><a class="icon-syllabus" style="color: black; text-decoration: none;"> Syllabus</a></h2>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p><strong>CREA E-110R Advanced Poetry Writing</strong></p>
<p><strong>Division of Continuing Education – Extension</strong></p>
<p><strong>Fall 2017 Online web conference</strong></p>
<p><strong>Wednesday 5:10pm - 7:10pm </strong></p>
<strong>David Barber (dbarber@fas.harvard.edu)</strong><br>
<p> </p>
<p>                              <span style="font-size: 10pt;">All the fun’s in how you say a thing.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt;">                                                                                          -- Robert Frost</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt;">                              Poetry is the peerless proficiency of the imagination.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 10pt;">                                                                                          – Marianne Moore</span></p>
<p><strong>Course Overview</strong></p>
<p>This intensive course in reading and writing poetry aims to help students acquire greater practical know-how and aesthetic conviction in the craft, with the overarching goal of making discernable progress toward a body of work to stand by. The guiding principle is that the more we understand about the structure of poetry, the more we appreciate the power of poetry: its visceral effect on body and mind, its kinetic interplay of sound and sense, its durable resonance as memorable speech, its prolific capacity for enchantment and enlightenment. Poetry is an expressive art with an immense history behind it, but it is also an exacting discipline that entails an adept working knowledge of its technical nomenclature, its tools of the trade, and its evolving traditions and ambitions. With that in mind, we will look closely at exemplary English and American poems of many kinds to see what they reveal about how poets work and play with the renewable resources of sound, rhythm, language, and form. We will also devote a good deal of time to appraising your own workmanship as you try your hand at writing and revising an assortment of poems drawing on certain fundamental principles and versatile techniques. To investigate how the eye, the ear, and the mind work in concert to produce artful poems of every variety, we will alternate constructive workshop sessions of student writing with the discussion of essays and poems by master poets. Listening to poems and saying them aloud will be an especially important component of the course. Students will also be asked to select two of their own “masters” to read in depth over the term, with the aim of gaining a sharper critical perspective on working toward an achieved style and a distinctive sensibility. The capstone of the course will be to assemble a portfolio of 12-15 poems that will be a mix of assigned and independent work. The ultimate goal is to have you all come away from our time together with a sharper ear for reading and writing in lines, a stronger grasp on how accomplished poems are conceived and constructed, and a deeper appreciation for why poetry matters.</p>
<p>              </p>
<p><strong>Texts and Readings</strong></p>
<p>There are three required texts for the course: Robert Pinsky’s <em>Singing School: Learning to Write (and Read) Poetry by Studying with the Masters</em> (Norton 2013), Edward Hirsch’s <em>The Essential Poet’s Glossary</em> (Mariner Books 20017), and <em>The Making of a Poem,</em> edited by Mark Strand and Eavan Boland (Norton 2001). In addition, there will be a number of assigned texts from the online course reader – short essays, sets of poems, optional exercises, handouts on technique and terminology – to help provide a shared frame of reference as we examine how sterling poems of various kinds are artfully designed and skillfully executed.</p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Course Requirements </strong></p>
<p><strong>1) Portfolio of poems</strong></p>
<p> Everyone will write a minimum of seven poems based on specific assignments. In addition, you’ll have the option of writing up to eight more poems that allow you to try your hand at other modes and forms of your own devising. We’ll read and discuss your drafts in class, and at the end of the term you’ll assemble your body of work into a course portfolio. I’ll be posting detailed guidelines for each assignment along with models drawn from the course anthology and class handouts. The idea in each case is to provide you with a blueprint for composing poems in keeping with particular structural principles and verse techniques, while at the same time giving you ample latitude for exploring your own affinities.</p>
<p> <strong>2) Recitation of a touchstone poem from memory</strong></p>
<p> Chances are it was a poet who first came up with that stirring metaphor for memorizing something exactly: learning it “by heart.” Certainly most poets would agree that one of the acid tests of an exemplary poem is whether it compels you to say it aloud, time and again. Consider this assignment an opportunity to pay homage to a poem that has proven to be just such a touchstone for you. Everyone will take a turn at reciting a poem for the class from memory (or as closely as possible), and say a few words about the aesthetic qualities that you feel make it a powerfully felt piece of writing.</p>
<p> <strong>3) Open-book quiz</strong></p>
<p> At the end of the term there will be an open-book quiz that will ask you to identify certain terms and forms essential to developing a good working knowledge of poetics and prosody. It’s primarily designed to be a test of your ear rather than your powers of analysis or rote learning: for the most part you’ll be sounding out a mixed bag of poems and passages and answering multiple-choice questions about their patterns of versification, their rhythmical structures, their diction and syntax, and their expressive use of line. There will likely be a handful of questions on conceptual ideas and historical terms (for example, the distinction between a metaphor and a simile, or the defining traits of a dramatic monologue), but the objective is not to have you regurgitate technical jargon so much as draw on what Robert Pinsky calls your “hearing-knowledge” to pick up on what any given set of lines are doing to earn their keep.</p>
<p><strong>4) Short report on two master poets</strong></p>
<p>An essential dimension of this advanced course will be the opportunity – some might say the obligation –  to take your cues from models and masters of your choosing. Early in the term everyone will select <strong>two </strong>poets of stature to read in depth on your own time. The general objective is to make a considered study of their respective bodies of work to sharpen your critical perspective on what T. S. Eliot famously called “tradition and the individual talent.” There will be a short paper due at the end of the term asking you to reflect on your findings.</p>
<p> Detailed guidelines for these assignments will be distributed well in advance of the due dates.</p>
<p><strong>Logistics &amp; Policies</strong></p>
<p>All assigned poems should be uploaded to the course dropbox by each Sunday at 9 pm. This uniform timetable will give us all time to look over the poems before we convene on Wednesday evenings. Extensions may be given for certain weeks on an individual basis, so long as you make the request by e-mail well in advance. You should plan to have each of your assigned poems workshopped at least briefly each week.</p>
<p>This course will adhere to the Harvard’s policies for attendance and academic integrity. (See below.) Final grades will be based on effort, improvement, attendance, class participation, and the quality of your writing. The quiz won’t be administered as a final exam, and will count for only a very small portion of your course grade.</p>
<h2><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Resources</strong></span></h2>
<p>The Academy of American Poets website (www.poets.org): Something for everyone – poems and profiles, forums and event calendars, and links to a host of literary journals and organizations.</p>
<p>Bartleby.com: A database of literature and poetry in the public domain. The site includes the work of a number of major English and American poets as well as an array of older Oxford poetry anthologies such as <em>Palgrave’s Golden Treasury</em> (1875), <em>The Oxford Book of Ballads</em> (1910), and <em>Metaphysical Lyrics and Poets</em> (1921). It also provides links to notable reference works like <em>The Oxford Shakespeare, Bartlett’s Familiar Quotations, Gray’s Anatomy</em>, and Strunk’s <em>Elements of Style</em>.</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Essential American Poets: Audio and Podcasts. Recordings of poets reading their own work on the Poetry Foundation website. (www.poetryfoundation.org/features/audio?show=Essential%20American%20Poets)</p>
<p> </p>
<p>Favorite Poem Project website (www.favoritepoem.org): An eclectic archive of video clips featuring “Americans saying poems they love,” the brainchild of former US poet laureate Robert Pinsky.</p>
<p>Woodberry Poetry Room (http://hcl.harvard.edu/poetryroom/): Harvard’s special collections reading room and audio archive for poetry, located in the Lamont Library.</p>
<p>Additional links to audio and video sites will also be posted from week to week.</p>
<br>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Writing Program policies on attendance and completion of work:</strong></p>
<p>Attendance:  Because Writing Program courses proceed by sequential writing activities, your consistent attendance for our conferences is essential.  If you are absent without medical excuse more than once, you are eligible to be officially excluded and failed.  On your first unexcused absence, you will receive a letter from me warning you of your situation.</p>
<p>Completion of Work:  Because your writing course is a planned sequence of writing, you must write all of the assignments to pass the course and you must write them within the schedule of the course--not in the last few days of the term after you have fallen behind.  If you fail to submit work when it is due, you will receive a letter from me reminding you of these requirements.  The letter will specify the new due date by which you must submit the late work.  If you fail to submit at least a substantial draft of the piece of writing by this new due date, you are eligible to be excluded from the course and failed.</p>
<p>The Summer School’s statement on plagiarism, from the “Student Responsibilities” section of the Summer School website:</p>
<p>Plagiarism:  Plagiarism is the theft of someone else’s ideas and work. It is the incorporation of facts, ideas, or specific language that are not common knowledge, are taken from another source, and are not properly cited. Whether you copy verbatim or simply rephrase the ideas of another without properly acknowledging the source, the theft is the same. A computer program written as part of your academic work is, like a paper, expected to be your original work and subject to the same standards of representation. In the preparation of work submitted to meet course, program, or school requirements—whether a draft or a final version of a paper, project, take-home exam, computer program, placement exams, application essay, oral presentation, or other work—you must take great care to distinguish your own ideas and language from information derived from sources. Sources include published and unpublished primary and secondary materials, the Internet, and information and opinions of other people.</p>
You are expected to follow the standards of proper citation and to avoid plagiarism. Please consult the Harvard Guide to Using Sources, prepared by the Harvard College Writing Program, for a helpful introduction to all matters related to source use: identifying and evaluating secondary sources, incorporating them into your work, documenting them correctly, and avoiding plagiarism. We also recommend that you complete our online tutorials “Using Sources, Five Scenarios” and “Using Sources, Five Examples” before you submit any written work. These tutorials take 15 minutes each to complete, and they will help you learn what you don't know about using sources responsibly. In cases of suspected plagiarism, student papers may be submitted to a private contracted service that reviews content for originality. Results from this review may be used to inform the Dean of Students Office in its inquiry. Papers submitted to this service are retained by that company and become part of their database of materials used in future searches. No personal identifying information is submitted or retained by the se</td>
</tr>
